1.title: Multi-attribute decision
1.notes:
Scenario 4: In this example, we consider the task where a participant can examine cues that are positioned on a bicycle. The participants have to click on cues to see them.
To customize the display, we need first to set the parameter *_customDisplay* to true. Then, we have to work with the “Content” of the screen, where we create both options and cues elements. For each of the options that participants can click to make a decision, we need to define an `id` that corresponds to the internal name of the option. The id can be set for any HTML element, giving you freedom to decide what the element should look like: it can be a text, an image, or a field. To display cues, you should create two divs: a wrapper and an inner one. For the wrapper, set the `id` with the following pattern: *“option name”* – *“cue name”*. The second inner div should be inside the wrapper. Within this inner div, you can place any elements, which will be displayed on click (if the paradigm is the closed Mouselab).
